SIMPLE: platitude
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Platitude
<hw>Plat"i*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from
<ets>plat</ets> flat. See <er>Plate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
quality or state of being flat, thin, or insipid; flat commonness;
triteness; staleness of ideas of language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To hammer one golden grain of wit into a sheet of infinite
<qex>platitude</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thought or remark which is flat, dull, trite, or
weak; a truism; a commonplace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Platitudinarian</ent>⟦br⟧
